PREDICTIVE MODELING — D208¶

TASK 2: LOGISTIC REGRESSION FOR PREDICTIVE MODELING¶

Part I: Research Question¶

A1: RESEARCH QUESTION:

What predictor variables are the major contributors for a customer to likely churn?

A2: OBJECTIVES AND GOALS:

The objective of predictive modeling is to implement a statistical technique using historical data to create, process, and validate a model to predict future results (Frankenfield, 2021).

In the business world, such as subscription-based businesses like telecommunication, internet, and TV channels providers, a constant battle exists to satisfy customers and prevent them from churning. A churn is when a customer stops or cancels a subscription (Gold & Tzuo, 2020).

The goals are to prevent customers from abandoning the business and acquire more customers based on the correlated variables. For example, suppose we established that higher-income customers tend to stay with the company longer, the company will then focus on that demographic of customers from not leaving the business because the cost of acquiring new customers outweighs the cost of retaining the existing customers.

The main goal of building the predictive model is to help the company retain the customers who are likely to churn by trying to find what features of services highly correlate with churn and improve those features to make the customers stay with the company.

Part II: Method Justification¶

B. Describe multiple regression methods by doing the following:

B1: SUMMARY OF ASSUMPTIONS:

Summarize the assumptions of a multiple regression model.

The logistic regression model makes the following assumptions about the relationships among the dependent and independent variables(Bobbit, 2020):

  • The response variable is of binary type i.e yes or no, male or female, 1 or 0
  • There are no correlations among the predictor variables
  • There is little or no multicollinearity among the predictor variables
  • There are no extreme outliers
  • A linear relationship exists between the predictor and the logit of the target variables

  • More data is required to build a stable model

    The formula for multiple logistic regression is as follows:

    z = β$_{0}$ + β$_{1}$x$_{1}$ + β$_{2}$x$_{2}$ + ...+ β$_{i}$x$_{i}$ --> linear combination of features
    ###
    p(z) = $\frac{{1}}{1 + e^{-z}}$ --> logistic sigmoid function

Where z = linear combination of features , regression coefficients=β$_{i}$, x$_{i}$ = predictor variables, and p(z) = probability between 0 and 1

B3: APPROPRIATE TECHNIQUE:

  1. Explain why logistic regression is an appropriate technique to analyze the research question summarized in Part I.

Since the target variable is binary, logistic regression is the most appropriate technique to be used to answer the research question. The goal of the question is to find out the probability of whether a customer is likely to churn or not. This requires a major deviation from the concept of linear regression where the target variable can be any real number (either positve or negative). When dealing with a binary target, the minimum range is 0 and the maximum 1. This is demonstrated by the logit function above. For logistic regression based problems, a classification method will employed to find the what percentage of demographic of customers belong to which of the two categories: churn or not churn.

In logistic regression, the relationship between the target variable and the β parameters is not linear and because of that the least squares method would not work as in linear regression and therefore a method called maximum likelihood will be employed to estimate the probability of predicting the churn or not churn from the data available (Shmueli et al.,2020).

# Function to detect the outliers
def find_outliers(df):
  num_cols =  df.select_dtypes(include = np.number)
  plt.figure(figsize=(17,11))
  plt.xticks()
  
  for i,col in enumerate(num_cols,1):
    plt.subplot(5,4,i)
    sns.boxplot(df[col])
    # plt.ylabel(col)
    plt.suptitle(' Outliers Detection Boxplots ', fontsize=25)
    plt.tight_layout(pad=4)
    
  plt.show()
      
find_outliers(cleaned_churn)

There are 17 variables with outliers. Since outliers distort the facts about statistical findings, several ways are available to deal them. In this project I will keep the outliers as the dataset is small and customers actual number could be greater than one in the dataset and therefore it's better to avoid sampling bias by not removing customers that appear as outliers but they are the actual customers with varying economic backgrounds. For example, some customers are wealthy and therefore their lifestyles are different from the majority of the customers.

Discusion About Summary Statistics¶

The statistical summary of the dataset of the all the predictor variables indicates that on average a customer's household contains 2 children with a mean income of \$39,806.93 and standard deviations of 2.15 and \$28,199.92, respectively.The average age of a customer with the company is 53.1 with standard deviation of 20.7. On the other hand, when it comes to problems with the service, a customer experienced 10 outages per week on average with standard deviation of 2.98 and a mean of 0.4 of yearly equipment failure with standard deviation of 0.64. An average of 12.02 of emails were sent by the customer with the standard deviation of 3.03. A customer is charged a monthly fee of \$172.6 on average with standard deviation of \$42.94. When it comes to data useage, a mean of 3392.3 GB of data is used per year by a customer with a standard deviation of 2185.3 GB. Item1 through Item8 have roughly the same average of 3.49 and standard deviation of 1.02. Finally, a customer tends to be with the company for 34.5 months on average as indicated by the 'tenure' variable.

When establishing correlations among the variables, there is no indication that, for example, having a lot of children means high data usage as the correlation between the number of children and bandwidth of GB used a year is very weak (0.026). It's the same story across all other variables with the exception of the bandwidth of GB versus the customer’s tenure. These variables show a very strong correlation (0.99).

Creating Dummy Variables¶

Using the code below, the categorical variables in the dataset will be converted into the numerical variables because it's difficult to establish relationships among the variables if they are not all numerical. The method that will be used is the pandas's get_dummies() method. This method converts the values in the categorical variables to either 1 or 0. In linear regression, it's important to avoid multicollinearity that gets introduced when using the dummy variables and therefore any values of the variables that go beyond 1 will be discarded as shown by this formula: k-1 where k represents levels present in the categorical variable. For example in the Gender column, the levels are represent as 'Male' or 'Female'. So k is 2 and therefore the dummy variable is going to be 2 - 1 and that means we only need one variable to be included to linear regression equation.

# This function removes redundancies and creates dummy variables while also removing original categorical variables
def dummified(df, cat_columns):
  for x in cat_columns:
    dummies = pd.get_dummies(df[x], prefix=x, dummy_na=False, drop_first=True)
    df = df.drop(x, 1)
    df = pd.concat([df, dummies], axis=1)
  return df
cleaned_churn = dummified(cleaned_churn, cat_columns)

Validating No Multicollinearity Exists¶

Building a robust model that can be used for business decision-making purposes requires extensive mitigation techniques to tackle some underlying model's problems that don't show up during the model building processes but only later when the model is in the production environment and therefore wreak havoc in providing bad business insights and possibly contribute to customer attrition. To avoid such disasters, two approaches will be employed to make the model a reliable one: using a correlation heatmap and a variance inflation factor (VIF) method to counter multicollinearity problems.

  • Variance inflation factor (VIF) is the determination of how much variance of a coefficient is increased due to multicollinearity (Ott et al., 2016) and VIF ranges from 1 indicating no multicollinearity to 5 or 10 indicating multicollinearity. The formula below shows how VIF is calculated for each predictor variable.

    VIF$_{k}$ = 1 / ( 1 - R$^{2}$$_{k}$ )

where VIF$_{k}$ is VIF for variable k, and R$^{2}$$_{k}$ is the coefficient of determination for the variable k.

By plotting the correlation matrix below, one of the assumptions about the logistic regression is validating that no or little multicollinearity among the predictor variables.

There are could be some predictor variables that have some multicollinearity and therefore must be removed. By discarding the variables with multicollinearity, we get one step closer in meeting one of the assumptions of logistic regression.

The heatmap below shows the correlation among the predictor variables. Once the variables with high correlation are identified, another heatmap is used to show their high correlations in much detail to justify their removal.

# **Source: https://etav.github.io/python/vif_factor_python.html**

import statsmodels.api as sm
from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor
# Function to check Variance Inflation Factor
def check_VIF(df):
  df = cleaned_churn.drop(columns=['Churn'])
  vif = pd.DataFrame()
  vif["features"] = df.columns
  vif["VIF Factor"] = [variance_inflation_factor(df.values, i) for i in range(df.shape[1])]
  
  return vif.round(1)

check_VIF(cleaned_churn)

D2: JUSTIFICATION OF MODEL REDUCTION:

Justify a statistically based variable selection procedure and a model evaluation metric to reduce the initial model in a way that aligns with the research question.

In generalized regression models, there are many methods to reduce the number of predictor variables in the dataset. One of the approaches applied to our dataset is the use of p-value. The p-value method decreases the number of variables to their most statistically significant features so that the model can improve the prediction accuracy and provide better interpretation by using a smaller subset of variables that have strongest effects(Hastie et al., 2017).

By comparing and contrasting the initial and reduced models, the p-values can be determined and the model is further reduced if the p-values are above the threshold of 0.05.

Part V: Data Summary and Implications¶

F. Summarize your findings and assumptions by doing the following:

F1: RESULTS:

Discuss the results of your data analysis, including the following elements:

Regression Equation for the Reduced Model¶

Here's the equation representing the reduced regression model:

Churn = -0.0004 + 0.00001Income - 0.0004Contacts - 0.05Tenure + 0.00001Techie - 0.0003Contract_One year - 0.0003Contract_Two Year - 0.0002Port_modem - 0.00012OnlineBackup - 0.000122DeviceProtection - 0.00012TechSupport - 0.00025PaperlessBilling

Interpretation of Coefficients of the Statistically Significant Variables of the Model¶

There are 11 variables that are statistically significant as their p-values are below 0.05: Income, Contacts, Tenure, Techie, Contract_One_year, Contract_Two_year, Port_modem, OnlineBackup,DeviceProtection, TechSupport, and PaperlessBilling. With the exception of Income and Techie variables' coefficients, all the other variables' coefficients are negatively contributing to the target variable, Churn. The positive coefficients indicate that if all variables in the model are equal, customers with levels of income and being techie are more likely to churn than other customers(Gold & Tzuo, 2020).

The Statistical and Practical Significance of the Model¶

Since the p-values of the significant variables are below the threshold of 0.05, they are statistically significant because there exists a relationship among the predictor and target variables and therefore it is not by chance they are related.

Because the model's accuracy is 0.76, the model is practically signicant as the variables in the dataset tend to relate to customers' likelihood of churning or not.

Limitations of the Data Analysis¶

Even though the model's accuracy is somewhat acceptable when predicting the outcome, churn, it's hard to justify the inclusion or exclusion of some variables as they lack practical application when predicting the target variable (the case of overfitting). For example, some categorical variables create overfitting problems in the application of multiple regression model as they require steps to first convert them into numerical variables which reduces the degree of freedom. The number of degree of freedom signifies the number of predictor variables of information present to predict the target variable and the less the number of predictor variables the less information to build a model that can generalize to other datasets and therefore the result is overfitting problems that limit the model's accuracy on other datasets(Nisbet et al., 2018).

F2: RECOMMENDATIONS:

From the equation of the reduced model,income and techie variables have positive coefficients. These would suggest that that customers in these two categories have higher influence in determining the chances of being churned and therefore the company should strive to provide better data plans coupled with improved extra services like data storage, device protection, and conservation of environment by encouraging the customers to use paperless billing. By taking into consideration all these variables, the company can be successful for a very long time.
